What does this mean for masks? If we think about the structure of a standard surgical mask, it has 3 layers. The outermost layer is made of polypropylene plastic, and its job is to absorb droplets and hold them in place, sequestering them away from your nose and mouth.

Water on a paper towel will spread from the center of the droplet outward. This is also true of droplets containing virus particles. As the moisture recedes, the envelope proteins are more likely to lose the water they need to maintain their function.
Water on a hard surface will stay in droplet form and slowly evaporate over time. Water on a paper towel, for example, will be soaked up by the paper and wicked away.
The virus can survive for much longer on hard surfaces like door knobs and bathroom counters than on soft items like clothing. Let's think about this from the perspective of a droplet of water.
COVID-19 is a coronavirus, which needs a special envelope to be able to infect a host cell. This envelope is made of protein, and needs to stay hydrated in order to be effective.

literally EVERY year, our graduate assistant union has to renegotiate with UF to talk them out of raising the already insane student fees. EVERY year.
The point of this thread is to say that graduate students deserve better. We deserve more support and fair pay for the labor we do.
We are expected to work full time, but we don't get paid for the labor we actually put in. We are classified as 0.5 FTE. We get paid as half-time employees.
That's almost $9k a year, minimum. How are we supposed to afford that? Even then, when there are holidays or campus closures, the centers close even though the parents still have to work.

Childcare is not included in a grad student's appointment. The center on campus has a years long waiting list, and costs $100 per child to even apply. The registration fee is $250 and they ask for a supply fee of $100 annually. Child care costs range from $170-$210 a week.

We no longer pay student fees on this grant, but we have to pay $700 every quarter in taxes or risk being fined by the IRS. There is no institutional support to tell us this stuff. We are supposed to figure it out on our own.

If we are awarded a T32 training grant, the government and the university reclassify us as government contractors. This means our insurance coverage changes. Worker's compensation is no longer covered. We are considered self-employed and are given a 1099 form.

If you are lucky enough to be offered a fellowship, you're also lucky if it's more than $29k a year before taxes. UF assesses student fees on us. We give the university back ~$3000+ of our pay annually.
Graduate students are the true workforce of academic research. To think otherwise is arrogant.
